1.1 Markdown

â¢ Markdown is a lightweight markup language with plain text formatting syntax (Easy-to-read, easy-to-write plain text format). It is designed so that it can be converted to HTML and many other formats (e.g.Â PDF, MS Word .docx).

â¢ Example: https://github.com/seb951/rmarkdown_workshop/blob/master/README.md

â¢ It saves and executes code in order to generate fully reproducible reports in different of static and dynamic output formats.

â¢ Like other markup languages (e.g.Â HTML and Latex), it is completely independent from R.

1.2 R Markdown

â¢ An extension of the markdown syntax.

â¢ https://rmarkdown.rstudio.com/ (Yihui Xie)

â¢ Plain text files that typically have the file extension .Rmd.

â¢ Written using an extension of markdown syntax that enables R code to be embedded in them in a way which can later be executed.

â¢ The R package rmarkdown package feeds the .Rmd file to knitr, which executes all of the code chunks and creates a new markdown (.md) document which includes the code and output.

â¢ Subsequently tranformed into .html/.tex/.docx by pandoc. Note that .tex files need to be transformed by pdflatex into .pdf files. Weâll come back to that later.

â¢ rmardown, knitr, and pandoc are built in Rstudio. pdflatex is not.

â¢ When you click the Knit button (top left), a document will be generated that includes both content as well as the output of any embedded R code chunks within the document.

3 Metadata (YAML Ainât Markup Language )

---
title: "Rmarkdown"
author: "Sebastien Renaut"
date: '2018-03-12'
output: html_document
---

â¢ Why YAML (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/YAML#History_and_name) ?

â¢ It specifies what kind of document will be created, and the options chosen.

â¢ It is not required (defaults then apply).

â¢ It uses Python-style indentation to specify certain options.

â¢ Many options possible depending what type of document you are generating. See below for some examples.

â¢ Note that several options can be specified either for the whole document (in the YAML header), or the code chunks, or both (chunks options supersede YAML header).

3.1 Customizing metadata

---
title: "Rmarkdown"
author: "Sebastien Renaut"
date: "September 25, 2018"
output:
html_document:
highlight: tango
number_sections: T
theme: united toc: yes
toc_depth: 3
---

3.2 Output types

See the documentation for more information. But these are some formats of interest.
â¢ html_document

â¢ ioslides_presentation

â¢ pdf_document - This will require that you have a Latex software installed - (We may get to that later).

â¢ word_document (.docx)

â¢ interactive shiny apps (We may get to that later).

3.3 Table of content options

â¢ toc: yes Generate TOC.

â¢ toc_depth:3 depth of TOC.

â¢ number_sections:T Add section numbering to headers (e.g., number_sections: true).

3.4 Theme, highlight, tabs, other options

â¢ theme: specifies the theme to use for the page (âceruleanâ, âjournalâ, âflatlyâ, âreadableâ, âspacelabâ, âunitedâ, and âcosmoâ).

â¢ highlight = Syntax highlighting style (e.g. âtangoâ, âpygmentsâ, âkateâ, âzenburnâ).

â¢ include If FALSE, knitr will run the chunk but not include the chunk in the final document.
â¢ See this Reference guide.

4 Code chunks

â¢ Code Chunk output can be customized with knitr options, arguments set in the {} of a chunk header.

â¢ Below, I use five arguments. These can be redefined later.

â¢ include = FALSE prevents code and results from appearing in the finished file. R Markdown still runs the code in the chunk, and the results can be used by other chunks.

â¢ echo = FALSE prevents code, but not the results from appearing in the finished file. This is a useful way to embed figures.

â¢ message = FALSE prevents messages that are generated by code from appearing in the finished file.

â¢ warning = FALSE prevents warnings that are generated by code from appearing in the finished file.

â¢ fig.cap = "..." adds a caption to graphical results.

â¢ fig.width=..., fig.height=... to change figure width/heigth.

â¢ Also, try clicking the green arrow on the right to execute code.

â¢ see cheat sheet for more info.

#This is an example using include = T, message = T, warning=T, echo = T, fig.cap="Figure 1".
x = rexp(1000)
min(x)
## [1] 0.0004176227
max(x)
## [1] 7.013993
plot(x)

Figure 1

5 Formatting basics

Markdown provides an easy way to make standard types of formatted text, like:

â¢ Two spaces for a newline character

â¢ italics (*text*) or italics (_text_)

â¢ bold

â¢ backslash (\) to interpret a special characters as character

â¢ bold italix

â¢ code

â¢ links

â¢ â&nbsp;â character for extra line spacing

â¢ See the cheatsheet

5.1 Equations/math symbols (from LaTeX typesetting language)

â¢ Mathematical material is set off by the use of single dollar-sign characters. Consequently, if you wish to use a dollar sign (for example, to indicate currency), you need to preface it with a back-slash.

â¢ \(E = mc^{2}\)

â¢ \(\sum_{i=1}^n ASV\)

â¢ \(F_{(1,69)}\) = 1.27, p-value=0.26

â¢ \(A = \pi*r^{2}\)

â¢ \(\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}\)

â¢ The use of double dollars quote allows for displayed formulas. \[X_i\]

â¢ See these for more examples.

5.2 References, footnotes, bibliography

â¢ Footnotes are easy when you have a few references1

â¢ Otherwise, you may specify a bibliography in the YAML metadata header.

...
csl: csl/peerj.csl
bibliography: biblio/test_library.bib
---

â¢ Example: Gapped BLAST and PSI-BLAST: a new generation of protein database search programs (Altschul et al., 1997) has been cited nearly 70,000 times!

â¢ These are just random references (eg. Thibert-Plante & Hendry, 2010; Wagner et al., 2012; Yoshida et al., 2014)

â¢ Citations go inside square brackets and are separated by semicolons. Each citation must have a key, composed of â@â + the citation identifier from the database.

â¢ A minus sign (-) before the @ will suppress mention of the author in the citation. This can be useful when the author is already mentioned in the text.

â¢ The Citation Style Language (.csl) file specifies the reference format.

â¢ It is an open XML-based language to describe the formatting of citations and bibliographies. Reference management programs using .csl include Zotero, Mendeley and Papers.

â¢ Here I just googled and download the .csl file for PeerJ.

â¢ Most journals should be on this github repo. But you could create your own (Yet Another Citation Formatâ¦)

â¢ A .bib file will contains the bibliographic information of our document. Here: a .bib file was created in the reference management software Papers3.

5.4 Including Tables

â¢ By default, R Markdown displays data frames and matrixes as they would be in the R terminal (in a monospaced font). It is not very pretty.

â¢ If you prefer that data be displayed with additional formatting you can use the knitr::kable function, as in the .Rmd file below.

#default R printout (ugly)
print(head(mtcars))
##                    mpg cyl disp  hp drat    wt  qsec vs am gear carb
## Mazda RX4         21.0   6  160 110 3.90 2.620 16.46  0  1    4    4
## Mazda RX4 Wag     21.0   6  160 110 3.90 2.875 17.02  0  1    4    4
## Datsun 710        22.8   4  108  93 3.85 2.320 18.61  1  1    4    1
## Hornet 4 Drive    21.4   6  258 110 3.08 3.215 19.44  1  0    3    1
## Hornet Sportabout 18.7   8  360 175 3.15 3.440 17.02  0  0    3    2
## Valiant           18.1   6  225 105 2.76 3.460 20.22  1  0    3    1
#kable from knitr (better looking)
library(knitr)
kable(head(mtcars),digits =1,caption = "An motorcars table")
